results.notes:
MACRO:
Right behind ocean dunes, amongst Pinus pinea, P. pinaster and native sandy bushes (Corema album, Helychrisum italicum). Abundant, in troops, often in clearings where the trees first appear, but sometimes completely exposed in the dunes.
Smell spermatic, taste indistinct to maybe spermatic

Pileus quite dark, dark brown to almost black, often with whitish velipellis at center when young, later disappearing and exposing a light brown rather smooth surface. Cuticle silky fibrillose to lanose when young, later becoming smoother, only very weakly rimose or cracking, or not at all. Hemispherical to plane or very slightly recurved with age (then sometimes slightly striate), without umbo or with low and irregular (off-center) umbo. Some remnants of veil on the margin in very young specimens, but no cortina ever observed.

Stipe often deeply buried in the loose sandy soil, with only the pileus popping out above ground level. Fibrillose when young to rather smooth in age, except the heavy pruinosity seen all the way down to the slightly recurved base, sometimes very slightly enlarged but never bulbose. Whitish-yellowish with apex often darker (redder, browner), lighter at the base.

Context white, unchanging in stipe, rather translucid in pileus.

MICRO:
- Spores ovoid-ellipsoid, often with (sub)conical apex. Very rarely cilindrical-navicular-laceroid.
(9.1) 10.6 – 12.7 (13.9) × (5.9) 6.3 – 7.4 (8.1) µm
Q = (1.4) 1.5 – 1.8 (2.1) ; N = 50
Me = 11.5 × 6.9 µm ; Qe = 1.7

- Pleurocystidia common but not abundant, lageniform to fusiform and quite crystaliferous, rarely clavate and then less crystaliferous. Walls ammonia negative to weakly positive.
(60.8) 60.84 – 70.48 (70.5) × 14.4 – 21.2 µm
Q = 3.2 – 4.4 ; N = 5
Me = 66 × 18.4 µm ; Qe = 3.6

- Abundant cheilocystidia, chubbier, more clavate-fusiform-utriform, less crystaliferous than pleurocystidia, sometimes subcapitate.

- Lower and 2nd third stipe mostly with disperse but common short clavate cystidioids, but also few more differentiated with thicker wall or larger cells.

- Upper stipe with abundant cystidia of all shapes, many short/clavate, many well developed, some even crystaliferous like pleurocystidia, some short/bulky with thick wall and crystals, many ogive-shaped or with short necked like a nipple (utriform), many are twisted distorted.

- Stipe apex like upper third but perhaps more abundant and clustered cystidia.
